// SPDX-License-Identifier: Apache-2.0 WITH LLVM-exception
//
// test/parse/recovery/two-top-level-errors.test — M2 Phase 5 / US3
// (T049 of `specs/005-m2-parser/tasks.md`).
//
// **Specification anchors**:
//   - spec.md FR-019 (DiagnosticEngine sole emitter), FR-020/FR-021
//     (recovery framework + multi-error fixture corpus minimum).
//   - parser-recovery.contract.md §"Multi-error fixture corpus
//     minimum" item 1: "two independent syntax errors in separate
//     `top_level_item`s … both diagnostics emitted in source order;
//     well-formed `top_level_item`s between/after the errors still
//     appear in the AST."
//   - /speckit-clarify session 2026-04-27 Q1 → Option A: full
//     multi-error recovery at every grammar level (clangd-style).
//
// This fixture exercises the top-level `parseCompilationUnit()`
// recovery scope: per the contract's recovery-set table, the default
// recovery set at the top level is
// `{struct, declare, module, param_int, param_str, Eof}`. After the
// first malformed `struct` raises its diagnostic, recovery MUST
// resume at the next `module` keyword and parse the SECOND malformed
// item, raising its own diagnostic.
//
// Per `nslc-emit-ast.contract.md` step 5 — when any error fires, NO
// AST is printed to stdout. So this fixture asserts ONLY:
//   (a) two error-severity diagnostic lines on stderr (in source
//       order),
//   (b) exit 1.
// The "partial-AST-preservation" property (well-formed siblings
// remain in the parent's vector) is a unit-test concern — see
// `test_unit/recovery_set_test/recovery_partial_ast_test.cpp` (T053).
//
// **FR-029 / Principle VIII RED state evidence**: against parent
// commit `39cc618` (M2 Phase 3+4 fully green), the parser does
// single-error bail — `parseCompilationUnit()` returns `nullptr` on
// the first syntax error, so only ONE diagnostic emits and the
// second `ERR-DAG` directive below FAILS to match. That observed
// failure IS the FR-029 evidence. Track L (T056–T058) lands the
// `RecoveryGuard` + `skipUntil()` framework; this fixture flips
// green at T059 (the green-on-implementation checkpoint).

// RUN: not %nslc -emit=ast %s 2>&1 | FileCheck %s --check-prefix=ERR

// First top-level item: malformed `struct` — the body has no closing
// `}` and no `;`. The parser MUST emit a diagnostic at the `module`
// keyword's location (where it expected a closing brace or struct
// member) and recover at the `module` token (top-level recovery set).
struct broken_struct {
module foo {
//      ^ Recovery resumes here. The second item is *also* malformed:
//        the body declares a `reg q` with no `;`, so a SECOND
//        diagnostic must emit before the parser bails to EOF.
    reg q
}

// Per the contract's "Diagnostic output during recovery" §, every
// diagnostic uses the canonical M1 form
// `<path>:<line>:<col>: error: <message>`. We use ERR-DAG since the
// exact line:col coordinates depend on where the parser pins each
// raise site; what is load-bearing is that BOTH error lines emit in
// a single run (Q1's full-recovery contract).

// ERR-DAG: error: expected
// ERR-DAG: error: expected
